<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<task id="030" project="code-quality-and-assurance-r1">
  <metadata>
    <title>Refactor Program.cs into Feature Modules</title>
    <phase>4: Remediation</phase>
    <status>completed</status>
    <estimated-hours>4</estimated-hours>
    <dependencies>001, 008</dependencies>
    <blocks>035, 043</blocks>
    <tags>remediation, dotnet, refactoring, code-quality</tags>
  </metadata>

  <prompt>
    Refactor Program.cs (currently 1,940 lines) into feature module extension methods following the
    ADR-010 pattern. Extract logical groupings into dedicated files under a DependencyInjection/ folder:
    AddSpaarkeCore(), AddDocumentsModule(), AddWorkersModule(), AddAiModule(), and any other natural
    groupings identified during audit. Program.cs must be under 500 lines after the refactor. Each
    module extension method file must be under 200 lines. Functionality must be identical before and
    after — this is a pure structural refactor with no behavioral changes.
  </prompt>

  <role>
    Senior .NET developer specializing in .NET 8 Minimal API architecture and dependency injection
    patterns. Expert in applying ADR-010 DI minimalism and feature module extraction.
  </role>

  <goal>
    A refactored Program.cs of under 500 lines that delegates DI registration to feature module
    extension methods, each in their own file under DependencyInjection/. All existing functionality
    is preserved — the build passes, all tests pass, and the API behaves identically. The DI
    registration count per module stays within the ADR-010 limit of 15 non-framework services.
  </goal>

  <context>
    <background>
      The BFF API Program.cs has grown to 1,940 lines across multiple AI-assisted development cycles.
      The audit (task 001) identified specific section boundaries and DI registration groupings that
      map naturally to feature modules. The feature module pattern in ADR-010 prescribes:

      ```csharp
      // In DependencyInjection/DocumentsModule.cs
      public static class DocumentsModule
      {
          public static IServiceCollection AddDocumentsModule(this IServiceCollection services)
          {
              services.AddSingleton<SpeFileStore>();
              services.AddSingleton<DocumentAuthorizationService>();
              // ... up to 15 non-framework registrations
              return services;
          }
      }
      ```

      Program.cs then becomes:
      ```csharp
      builder.Services
          .AddSpaarkeCore()
          .AddDocumentsModule()
          .AddWorkersModule()
          .AddAiModule();
      ```

      The audit report at projects/code-quality-and-assurance-r1/notes/audit-bff-api.md contains the
      section breakdown of Program.cs (which sections exist at which line ranges) — read this first
      to understand the natural extraction boundaries before starting.

      This is a pure structural refactor — no logic changes, no new services, no removed registrations.
      The goal is readability and maintainability, not functional change.
    </background>
    <relevant-files>
      <file>src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Program.cs (modify — primary target)</file>
      <file>src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/DependencyInjection/ (create — new folder for modules)</file>
      <file>projects/code-quality-and-assurance-r1/notes/audit-bff-api.md (read — section breakdown from task 001)</file>
    </relevant-files>
  </context>

  <constraints>
    <constraint source="ADR-010">Each module extension method must have no more than 15 non-framework DI registrations. If a logical group exceeds this limit, split it into sub-modules (e.g., AddDocumentsCoreModule + AddDocumentsStorageModule).</constraint>
    <constraint source="ADR-010">Use concrete types by default — do not introduce new interfaces during this refactor. If an interface currently exists with a single implementation, note it but do not remove it in this task (that is task 031 scope).</constraint>
    <constraint source="spec">Program.cs MUST be under 500 lines after refactor. Each DependencyInjection/*.cs file MUST be under 200 lines.</constraint>
    <constraint source="spec">This is a structural refactor only — zero behavioral changes. No service is added, removed, or reconfigured. All existing middleware, pipeline configuration, and endpoint registration must remain identical.</constraint>
    <constraint source="testing.md">Run `dotnet build` before starting (establish baseline) and after each extraction (verify no regression). Run `dotnet test` after all extractions are complete to verify functional equivalence.</constraint>
  </constraints>

  <knowledge>
    <files>
      <file>.claude/adr/ADR-010.md</file>
      <file>projects/code-quality-and-assurance-r1/notes/audit-bff-api.md</file>
      <file>.claude/constraints/testing.md</file>
    </files>
  </knowledge>

  <steps>
    <step order="1">Read projects/code-quality-and-assurance-r1/notes/audit-bff-api.md to get the Program.cs section breakdown (line ranges and logical groupings identified during the audit). Use this as the extraction plan.</step>
    <step order="2">Run `dotnet build src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/` to establish a clean baseline. Record the output. Zero errors required before proceeding.</step>
    <step order="3">Read Program.cs in full and map the actual sections to the audit report's breakdown. Identify 4-6 natural feature module groupings based on related service registrations and functionality.</step>
    <step order="4">Create the DependencyInjection/ folder under src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/. Plan the module files: list the module names, their extension method names, and which DI registrations each will contain.</step>
    <step order="5">Extract the first module (start with the largest grouping to get the biggest line-count reduction). Create the .cs file, move the relevant registrations, update Program.cs to call the extension method. Build to verify.</step>
    <step order="6">Extract the second module. Build to verify. Continue this one-module-at-a-time approach with a build check after each extraction.</step>
    <step order="7">Extract remaining modules until Program.cs is under 500 lines. Maintain build verification after each extraction.</step>
    <step order="8">Verify each module file is under 200 lines. If any module exceeds 200 lines, split it using a sub-module pattern (AddXxxCoreModule + AddXxxStorageModule or similar).</step>
    <step order="9">Run `dotnet build src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/` on the complete refactored codebase. Must produce zero errors and zero new warnings.</step>
    <step order="10">Run `dotnet test` to verify all tests pass after the structural refactor. Record test results.</step>
    <step order="11">Count the final line count of Program.cs (`wc -l src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Program.cs`) and each DependencyInjection/*.cs file. Verify all limits are met.</step>
    <step order="12">Update TASK-INDEX.md: change task 030 status from pending to completed.</step>
  </steps>

  <outputs>
    <output type="file">src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Program.cs (refactored, under 500 lines)</output>
    <output type="directory">src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/DependencyInjection/ (new — 4-6 module files)</output>
  </outputs>

  <acceptance-criteria>
    <criterion>Program.cs is under 500 lines after refactor</criterion>
    <criterion>Each file in DependencyInjection/ is under 200 lines</criterion>
    <criterion>At minimum four module extension methods exist: AddSpaarkeCore, AddDocumentsModule, AddWorkersModule, AddAiModule (or equivalent groupings)</criterion>
    <criterion>No non-framework DI registration in any module exceeds 15 services</criterion>
    <criterion>`dotnet build src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/` produces zero errors and zero new warnings</criterion>
    <criterion>`dotnet test` passes with the same results as before the refactor</criterion>
    <criterion>No new interfaces were introduced during the refactor</criterion>
    <criterion>No existing middleware, pipeline configuration, or endpoint registration was changed</criterion>
    <criterion>TASK-INDEX.md updated to reflect task completion</criterion>
  </acceptance-criteria>
</task>
